ce:section.ce:para:
The results for the zones of inhibition (ZOI) measured (
                        Fig. 10

                        ) corresponded to the results of the CFU, where ZnO-NRs nanohybrids showed better antimicrobial activity. This is correlated to the morphology and the proposed antimicrobial activity of the nanohybrids which allow better internalization of the nanohybrid. The maximum zone of inhibition was for ZnO-NRs@GQDs against S. aureus (40 mm ± 2 mm) followed by ZnO-NRs@GQDs against E.coli (37 mm ± 2 mm). On the other hand, minimum zone of inhibition was for the bare ZnO-NFs against E. coli (11 mm ± 2 mm) zero inhibition when both ZnO-NFs and the nanohybrid ZnO-NFs@GQDs were tested against Pseudonmosa was observed, we attribute this to the cell morphology of Gram-negative bacteria. Except for the ZnO-NFs and ZnO-NFs@GQDs tested against Pseudonmosa, we observed a trend that incorporating the GQDs resulted in enhanced the antimicrobial properties of the nanohybrid. The distinct rod shape of both the ZnO-NRs and ZnO-NRs@GQDs nanohybrid allowed better penetration in the bacterial membrane which resulted in gradual damage of the respiratory enzymes and cytoplasmic contents which resulted in the death of bacterial cells [25].
